{\plain \fs26 \b\fs26 John Paul II and the Universal Call to Personalist Feminism }{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \par
}{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \line }{\plain \fs26 \b\fs26 \par
}{\plain \fs26 \b\fs26 R. Mary Hayden Lemmons, Ph.D.}{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \par
}{\plain \fs26 \b\fs26 University of St. Thomas}{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \par
}\pard \fs26
{\plain \fs26 \fs26  \par
}{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \par
}{\plain \fs26 \fs26 \tab }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Contemporary culture is convinced that the Catholic Church oppresses women insofar as the fulfillment of \softline
women is deemed to require abortion and no distinction between gender roles.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 1{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 1}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Consider, for instance,  the United State Supreme Court{\u8217\'92}s decision in }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Casey: }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 "the ability of women to participate \softline
equally in the economic and social life of the Nation has been facilitated by their ability to control their reproductive \softline
lives" [through abortion]. }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Planned Parenthood of Southeastern Pennsylvania v. Casey. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 505 U.S. 833 (U.S. Supreme \softline
Court, 1992).}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  But the Church would be oppressing \softline
women only if the Church were not calling all to honor the basic truths about women. This paper examines these \softline
basic truths as formulated by John Paul II in order to ascertain whether all are called to be personalist feminists.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 First truth: Men and Women are Equals\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab In his Apostolic Letter, }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 On the Dignity and Vocation of Women }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 (}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem, }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 hereafter }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 MD}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 ), John \softline
Paul II points out that the absolute equality of men and women }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is required by }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  1:27: {\u8220\'93}God created man in His \softline
own image, in the image of God He created him; male and female He created them.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 2{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 2}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n.6: {\u8220\'93}At this point, however, we can say that the biblical account puts forth the truth about the \softline
personal character of the human being. }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Man is a person, man and woman equally so,}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  since both were created in the \softline
image and likeness of the personal God.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \i\super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20   }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Sexual equality is not only \softline
required by this text, it is also required by the theology of imaging God. For }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  1:27 claims not only that men \softline
and women equally image God, but that they also image Him as male and female. It is thus not necessary to be the \softline
same in order to be equal in being an image of God. John Paul II also argues that Christ affirms the equality of \softline
woman.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 3{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 3}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 n. 25: {\u8220\'93}Meditating on what the Gospels say about Christ{\u8217\'92}s attitude towards women, we can \softline
conclude that as a man, a son of Israel, he revealed the dignity of the {\u8220\'93}daughters of Abraham{\u8221\'94} (cf. Lk 13:16), the \softline
dignity belonging to women from the very {\u8220\'93}beginning{\u8221\'94} on an equal footing with men.{\u8221\'94} [sic]. For an elaboration of \softline
what I call {\u8220\'93}the gender mission of Christ{\u8221\'94} see {\u8220\'93}Equality, Gender and John Paul II,{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Logos: A Journal of Catholic \softline
Thought and Culture}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  5:3 (2002): 111-130. For a more popular treatment see {\u8220\'93}Priesthood and the Masculinity of \softline
Christ{\u8221\'94} on-line at CatholicCulture.org at }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=6586.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Second truth: Women and Men Find Fulfillment in and through Love{}{\plain \fs24 \super 4{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 4}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 This section and the next draw heavily from my {\u8220\'93}Equality, Gender, and John Paul II,{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Logos: A Journal of Catholic \softline
Thought and Culture}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  5:3 (2002): 111-130.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  does not only proclaim sexual equality but it also proclaims that sexuality is designed for a \softline
heterosexual union able to image God. How so? John Paul II explains: \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 If  . . . we wish to draw also from the narrative of the Yahwist text the concept of {\u8220\'93}image of God,{\u8221\'94} we can 
then deduce that man became the {\u8220\'93}image and likeness{\u8221\'94} of God not only through his own humanity, but also \softline
through the communion of persons which man and woman form right from the beginning. The function of \softline
the image is to reflect the one who is the model, to reproduce its own prototype. Man becomes the image of \softline
God not so much in the moment of solitude as in the moment of communion. He is . . . essentially an image \softline
of the inscrutable divine communion of Persons.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 5{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 5}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs18 \i\fs18 The General Audience}{\plain \fs18 \fs18  of Nov. 14, 1979 pp. 73-74 in }{\plain \fs18 \i\fs18 Original Unity of Man and Woman, }{\plain \fs18 \fs18 Boston: Daughters of St. Paul, 1981, \softline
n. 3.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab \tab \par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Accordingly, heterosexual love and spousal oneness image nothing less than the love and oneness of the Trinity, \softline
wherein the distinction of persons{\u8212\'97}and roles---preclude neither unity nor equality. As a result, any inequality \softline
between man and woman would distort this sacred Trinitarian image. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The spousal unification in love excels in imaging the triune God in the following ways: (1) by being a unit \softline
of }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 distinct }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  equals; (2) by being a unit constituted by love; and (3) by being fertile in the generation of new life.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 6{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 6}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8220\'93}The distinction and reciprocity of the human couple are a sign of God{\u8217\'92}s love not only as the basis of a vocation to \softline
communion, but also for the purpose of procreative fruitfulness.{\u8221\'94} John Paul II, General Audience of Feb. 7}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 th}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 , 2001, \softline
n. 4.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20    In \softline
this way, the loving heterosexual marriage not only images the Godhead but also His life of love. We live to love.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 7{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 7}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Cf}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 . Fides et Ratio}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 7: {\u8220\'93}As the source of love, God desires to make himself known; and the knowledge which the \softline
human being has of God perfects all that the human mind can know of the meaning of life.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Hence, the human vocation to love in the image of the Trinity bestows upon femininity and masculinity \softline
their proper meanings: self-transcendence through a fruitful love between distinct equals. This is the nuptial meaning \softline
of the human body: sexuality is for facilitating a fruitful Trinitarian-like love. Sex is for self-giving love. This is not \softline
to say however that sexual love is the fulfillment of love. It is rather to say that the fulfillment of love is finding a \softline
way to seek the good of others. The second basic truth is thus that women }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 (and men), find fulfillment in and through \softline
love.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Third basic truth: Male Oppression of Women Continues}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab John Paul II argues that due to Original Sin, men routinely oppress women and that Christ accordingly \softline
sought to restore woman to the equality, respect and dignity that was hers in the beginning, that is, before Original \softline
Sin.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 8{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 8}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 15: {\u8220\'93}Christ{\u8217\'92}s affirmation of the equality and dignity of woman, through . . .the Gospel of His \softline
words and deed, is a consistent protest against whatever offends the dignity of women.{\u8221\'94} Hence, the surprise and the \softline
dismay of others recorded in Jn 4:27 and Lk 7:39; hence also, the revolutionary character of his teaching against \softline
stoning women adulterers, divorce and lust recorded  in Jn 8:3-11, Mt. 19:3-8 and Mt 5:28, respectively.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  Original Sin, moreover, not only ruptured the relationship of human beings to God but also the relationship \softline
between men and women. }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  3:16 is quite explicit that some penalties of Original Sin are gender-specific, \softline
affecting even the spousal union of love:  {\u8220\'93}Your desire shall be for your husband, and he shall rule over you.{\u8221\'94}  In \softline
other words, Original Sin left woman with the desire to close her love in upon her husband and make him the source \softline
of her happiness, while Original Sin left men with the desire to dominate women. Yielding to either desire is the \softline
wellspring of sexual inequality and oppression. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The gender ramifications of Original Sin have yet to be fully recognized. Even some Christian marriages \softline
embody spousal inequality by unilaterally subordinating the wife to the husband.  In this regard, two passages are \softline
cited most frequently:}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20  Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  2:18-25 in which God declares that Adam will receive a helper fit for him; and }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Eph.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  \softline
5:22-23 in which wives are told to be submissive to their husbands.  Being a helper and being submissive can be \softline
understood either as a gender role peculiar to wives or as a spousal role common to both men and women. The first \softline
interpretation establishes an inequality that contradicts the equality required by }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  1:27. It also misunderstands \softline
the story of Adam and Eve. According to John Paul II, the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  text that brings woman forth from Adam{\u8217\'92}s rib 
confirms her equality.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 9{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 9}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem  }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 n. 6: {\u8220\'93}The biblical text provides sufficient bases for recognizing the essential equality of man \softline
and woman from the point of view of their humanity.}{\plain \fs16 \super\fs16 24}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8221\'94} [Footnote 24: {\u8220\'93}Among the Fathers of the Church who affirm \softline
the fundamental equality of man and woman . . . Origen . . .Clement of Alexandria . . .St. Augustine . . .{\u8221\'94}]}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20   Taking these texts as his guide, John Paul II argues that the Scriptural texts identifying the \softline
wife as helper and as submissive are to be understood as identifying spousal roles, rather than gender roles. As such, \softline
these texts require not only the man to be the wife{\u8217\'92}s helper,{}{\plain \fs24 \super 10{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 10}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   n. 7.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  but also to be submissive to her in Christ.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 11{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 11}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   n. 24.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  In the \softline
words of John Paul II: \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The author of the Letter to the Ephesians . . . {\u8216\'91}Wives, be subject to your husbands, as to the Lord. For the \softline
husband is the head of the wife{\u8217\'92} (5:22-23) . . . knows that this way of speaking, so profoundly rooted in the \softline
customs and religious tradition of the time, is to be understood and carried out in a new way: as a {\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 mutual \softline
subjection out of reverence for Christ{\u8221\'94}}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  (cf. Eph. 5:21). . . . in the relationship between husband and wife the \softline
{\u8216\'91}subjection{\u8217\'92} is not one-sided but mutual.  \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab In relation to the {\u8216\'91}old{\u8217\'92} this is evidently something {\u8216\'91}new{\u8217\'92}: it is an innovation of the Gospel. [sic]}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20   \softline
Mulieris Dignitatem }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 24.\par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Also:\par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 All of the reasons in favor of the {\u8220\'93}subjection{\u8221\'94} of woman to man in marriage must be understood in the \softline
sense of a {\u8220\'93}mutual subjection{\u8221\'94} of both {\u8220\'93}out of reverence for Christ.{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n.24.\par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 John Paul II{\u8217\'92}s interpretation of these Scriptural passages reveals a deep commitment to the equality of men and \softline
women.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab John Paul the Great also points out that the male temptation to dominate women is fed by sexual desires \softline
that are untamed by chastity and that values women as tools for self-gratification. A man{\u8217\'92}s lust thus confirms his \softline
dominating tendency and prevents the woman from being seen as man{\u8217\'92}s equal. As a result, lust and its \softline
presuppositions of inequality are especially destructive of spousal love which requires each spouse to be a gift of \softline
love for the other. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Lust and inequality block the ability of the husband to recognize the wife{\u8217\'92}s acts of love as gifts; rather, such \softline
husbands treat any act of love as acknowledgment of his superiority. In such relationships, there is nothing the \softline
woman can do that can be recognized as a spousal love-gift; her initiatives are misunderstood as attempts to gain \softline
power over the man; they are not perceived as}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20  inviting}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 an equal}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  to a union of love. As a writer to Ann Landers \softline
complained:{}{\plain \fs24 \super 12{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 12}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8221\'94}Reader: Women should accept man{\u8217\'92}s desire for more than one,{\u8221\'94} Letter to Ann Landers, Signed {\u8220\'93}The Truth Hurts \softline
in Austin, Texas.{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Star Tribune, }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 11 February 2001, sec. Variety, p. E2. This letter-writer also asserted: {\u8220\'93}Many other \softline
cultures openly accept polygamy.  . . . And in many countries, adultery is accepted and shrugged off as nothing to \softline
get excited about. The wife gets the financial support and social position, and the mistress gets the sex. This sounds \softline
like a fair exchange to me.{\u8221\'94} }}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The truth is, there is not a woman on the planet who can fully satisfy the needs of a powerful male. When \softline
women quit asking men to make them the center of their universe and learn to accept a strong man{\u8217\'92}s desire \softline
for more than one female companion, families will live together longer, more happily and with less rancor.\par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The prejudice, shown in this letter, shows how blinding male chauvinism can be. For this reason, chauvinism is not \softline
merely selfishness but a destroyer of interpersonal love between equals. As the Pope points out: \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 . . . {\u8220\'93}domination{\u8221\'94} indicates the disturbance and loss of the stability of that fundamental equality which the \softline
man and the woman possess in the {\u8220\'93}unity of the two{\u8221\'94} and this is especially to the disadvantage of the \softline
woman, whereas }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 only the equality }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 resulting from their dignity as persons can give to their mutual \softline
relationship the character of an }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 authentic}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  {\u8220\'93}communio personarum.{\u8221\'94}  }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   n. 10 (emphasis \softline
mine)\par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Equality, thus, for John Paul II, is a necessary presupposition to marital love.  Unless a man }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  affirms that a \softline
woman is his equal, her love can neither be recognized as a gift nor reciprocated; without reciprocation, an 
{\u8220\'93}authentic{\u8221\'94} spousal communion cannot be established. In other words, the man{\u8217\'92}s affirmation of a woman{\u8217\'92}s equality \softline
necessarily precedes her ability to be a gift of love to the man as well as the man{\u8217\'92}s ability to be a gift of love to the \softline
woman. Thanks to Original Sin, romantic love becomes a war-zone for egotistical power games rather than the \softline
opportunity for true love.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Thus, John Paul II{\u8212\'97}in order to protect the conditions necessary for spousal love{\u8212\'97}had to denounce sexual \softline
inequality both inside and outside of marriage. Indeed, lest we assume that the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  punishments are exhausted \softline
within the confines of marriage, John Paul the Great cautions us that the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Genesis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  punishments  {\u8220\'93}refer directly to \softline
marriage, but indirectly they concern the different spheres of social life: the situations in which the woman remains \softline
disadvantaged or discriminated against by the fact of being a woman.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 13{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 13}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 10.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20   Original sin is thus responsible for the male \softline
chauvinism that has caused so much suffering on the part of women who are valued as existing only for the sake of \softline
man{\u8212\'97}and not for her own sake.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Fourth Basic Truth: Ending the Mistreatment of Women is an Universal Obligation of Personalist Feminism}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The basic ethical obligation to love others as oneself obligates all to oppose injustice whenever feasible. \softline
This is especially the case with Christians who are called to resist the on-going and persistent effects of Original Sin \softline
including those effects that disadvantage women. Hence, since it is the task of feminism to counter whatever harms \softline
women, every Christian is called to be a feminist. But what type of feminism is obligatory? \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab We begin to identify the type of feminism that we should pursue by realizing that the all-encompassing \softline
Christian vocation is to love altruistically.  Altruistic love transcends the self. By so doing, altruistic love frees the \softline
self{}{\plain \fs24 \super 14{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 14}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8220\'93}. . . freedom is acquired in love, that is, in the gift of self.{\u8221\'94}}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Veritatis Splendor }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n.87}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  and restores one to oneself.  This means that feminism is to counter the effects of Original Sin through love. \softline
The obligation to treat human beings with love is called the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Personalistic Norm}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  by John Paul II.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 15{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 15}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Love and Responsibility 41.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   The feminism that \softline
seeks to remedy the disadvantages of women through love is thereby best called {\u8220\'93}Personalist Feminism.{\u8221\'94} \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Fifth Basic Truth: Personal Dignity is Protected & Restored through Merciful Love\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The love prescribed by the Personalistic Norm and Personalist Feminism is the love that protects and restores \softline
personal dignity. As such, this love is quintessentially merciful. As John Paul II put it:{}{\plain \fs24 \super 16{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 16}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 14.4:  {\u8220\'93}. . . love and only love (including the kindly love that we call {\u8216\'91}mercy{\u8217\'92}) is capable \softline
of restoring man to himself.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 . . . love and mercy bring it about that people meet one another in that value which is man himself, with the \softline
dignity that is proper to him. (}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  14.5)\par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Merciful love has several characteristics: it has the deepest respect for what is human and the sweetest sensitivity to \softline
the needs of the person; it is the spirit of mutual brotherhood; it extends cordial tenderness and sensitivity;{}{\plain \fs24 \super 17{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 17}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 14.6.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  it is 
forgiving;{}{\plain \fs24 \super 18{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 18}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  14.8 {\u8220\'93}Society can become {\u8216\'91}ever more human{\u8217\'92} only when we introduce . . . the moment of \softline
forgiveness . . . Forgiveness demonstrates the presence in the world of the love which is more powerful than sin. . . . \softline
A world [without forgiveness] would be nothing but a world of cold and unfeeling justice, in the name of which each \softline
person would claim his or her own rights vis-a-vis others; the various kinds of selfishness latent in man would \softline
transform life and human society into a system of possession of the weak by the strong, or into an arena of \softline
permanent strife between one group and another.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  it is the very form of God{\u8217\'92}s love for us.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 19{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 19}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia: }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 13.4: {\u8220\'93}It is precisely because sin exists in the world, which {\u8220\'93}god so loved . . .that he gave \softline
his only Son{\u8221\'94} that God, who {\u8220\'93}is love{\u8221\'94} cannot reveal himself otherwise than as mercy. This corresponds not only to \softline
the most profound truth of that love which God is, but also to the whole interior truth of man and of the world which \softline
is man{\u8217\'92}s temporary homeland.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  As such, it benefits the giver as well as the recipient.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 20{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 20}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 DM}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  14.30: {\u8220\'93}When we base ourselves on this disquieting model [of Christ crucified], we are able with all humility \softline
to show mercy to others, knowing that Christ accepts it as if it were shown to himself (Mt 25:43-40). An act of \softline
merciful love is only really such when we are deeply convinced at the moment that we perform it that we are at the \softline
same time receiving mercy from the people who are accepting it from us.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The awareness of mercy{\u8217\'92}s mutuality precludes prideful self-righteousness and arrogance by reinforcing the \softline
sacredness of the other that is so necessary for recognizing the other{\u8217\'92}s gift of self{\u8211\'96}especially in the case of woman. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Sixth Basic Truth: Merciful Love is Collaborative}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The mutuality of merciful love is experienced through collaboration. \tab Collaboration embodies mutuality \softline
because it requires seeking to remedy needs by working with others for the sake of others. And this concern for \softline
others identifies collaboration as instantiating love: after all, love cares about others and seeks to counter all evils. As \softline
John Paul II put it: love is an {\u8220\'93}anxious solicitude to ensure for each individual every true good and to remove and \softline
drive away every sort of evil.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 21{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 21}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  15.4.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Collaboration thus instantiates the personalistic norm to love others. Collaboration is, accordingly, an \softline
universal duty. As John Paul II pointed out: {\u8220\'93}Collaboration in the development of the whole person and of every \softline
human being is in fact a duty of all toward all.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 22{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 22}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Sollicitudo Rei Socialis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 32.2.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  This means that collaboration must structure the interactions of \softline
men and women. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Collaborative interactions, moreover, are required for discharging one{\u8217\'92}s obligation to the common good, \softline
which is nothing other than {\u8220\'93}the good of all and of each individual, because we are all really responsible for all.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 23{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 23}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs18 \i\fs18 Sollicitudo Rei Socialis}{\plain \fs18 \fs18  n. 38.6.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20   \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab To seek the true good of others in collaboration with others is to exercise solidarity. Collaborative solidarity \softline
seeks to serve rather than be served.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 24{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 24}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Sollicitudo}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 46.6: {\u8220\'93}The freedom with which Christ has set us free (cf. Gal 5:1) encourages us to become the \softline
}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 servants}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  of all. Thus the process of development and liberation takes concrete shape in the exercise of solidarity, that \softline
is to say in the love and service of neighbor; especially of the poorest . . .{\u8221\'94} }}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  It promotes autonomy and free-self-determination especially where it is \softline
systematically denied. It thus seeks to help the victims of poverty, prejudice, and male chauvinism. It thereby \softline
humanizes the world. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Seventh Basic Truth: Collaboration Humanizes the World}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The sixth basic truth cannot be denied without oppressing women, namely, that the collaborative love and \softline
solidarity required by Personalist Feminism humanizes the world. To so humanize the world through collaborative 
solidarity or providential love is precisely the mission of today{\u8217\'92}s Church.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 25{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 25}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Dives in Misericordia}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  14.7: {\u8220\'93}. . . Paul VI more than once indicated the {\u8216\'91}civilization of love{\u8217\'92} as the goal toward \softline
which all efforts in the cultural and social fields as well as in the economic and political fields should tend .}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20   As John Paul II pointed out ( }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Dives in \softline
Misericordia 14.7): {\u8220\'93}[T]he Second Vatican Council . . .  speaks repeatedly of the need to make the world more \softline
human and says that the realization of this task is precisely the mission of the Church in the modern world.{\u8221\'94} \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The obligation to humanize the world requires a commitment not only to end the oppression of all, but also \softline
a specific obligation to end the oppression of women through providential and collaborative love. And this is nothing \softline
other than to honor the subjectivity of women, that is, to respect them as persons with whom one is to collaborate in \softline
the providential pursuit of good. That is to say, it is to be a personalist feminist. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab To be a personalist feminist is to be one who counters the structures of evil according to the exigencies of \softline
one{\u8217\'92}s life and professional responsibilities. The practice of personalist feminism is especially binding upon \softline
professionals both men and women, because professionals build economic, educational, medical, political, legal, and \softline
other social institutions. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Although these institutions can benefit human beings and promote their happiness, they are not likely to do \softline
so. We are a fallen race. Careful review of our institutions are thus needed to ensure that they do not become \softline
{\u8220\'93}structures of sin.{\u8221\'94}  \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab John Paul points out that institutions are especially liable to becoming oppressive when they are not \softline
structured to acknowledge transcendent truths.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 26{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 26}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Centesimus Annus}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 44: {\u8220\'93}If there is no transcendent truth, in obedience to which a person achieves his full \softline
identity, then there is no sure principle for guaranteeing just relations between people. Their self-interest as a class, \softline
group or nation would inevitably set them in opposition to one another. If one does not acknowledge transcendent \softline
truth, then the force of power takes over, and each person tends to make full use of the means at his disposal in order \softline
to impose his own interests or his own opinion, with no regard for the rights of others. People are then respected \softline
only to the extent that they can be exploited for selfish ends.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  Only commitments to transcendental truths preclude exploitation. \softline
For this reason, failure to acknowledge the transcendent truth about human beings leads to totalitarianism {}{\plain \fs24 \super 27{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 27}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Cf. }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Centisimus Annus }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 n. 45.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 --even \softline
within democracies.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 28{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \super 28}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Centisimus Annus}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  n. 46.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20  }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Indeed, no institution{\u8211\'96}however small and intimate--escapes the threat of exploiting its \softline
members for institutional goals. It is thus necessary for social institutions to the transcendence of every individual. \softline
Institutions exist for the sake of persons, not persons for the sake of institutions.\tab \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Acknowledgment that persons transcend their institutions entails treating persons with a love that is both \softline
providential and collaborative. Such love calls every human being to realize that interdependency is essential to \softline
human beings: we are naturally social or relational beings. We become who we are meant to be through \softline
collaborative relationships of love{\u8212\'97}just as personalist feminism prescribes.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Eight Basic Truth: Personalist Feminism Seeks Solutions to Global Problems}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The call of personalist feminism, moreover, is global, since human interdependencies are also global. Every \softline
person is to be concerned with advancing the welfare of the other according to opportunities of time, place, financial \softline
resources, and talents. This means that professionals are especially called upon to address the problems cause by \softline
globalization. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab These problems are particularity acute for mothers with young children in the least developed countries.  \softline
According to Mary Ann Glendon, the framework for addressing these problems has been identified as having these \softline
elements: primary health care, nutrition and sanitation debt relief, fair trade practices, the rule of law, and investment \softline
in education.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 29{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 29}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8220\'93}Holy See Addresses U.N. Body on Poverty Eradication,{\u8221\'94}}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Zenit}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 News Agency, The World Seen from Rome}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 . July 1, \softline
2004 (Zenit.org) Code: ZE04070121.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20   \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab In brief: human dignity requires placing societies and economies within a juridical framework that 
subordinates the marketplace to the demands of morality, human rights, the common good, and human \softline
transcendence through love.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  In this regard, John Paul II emphasizes the importance of natural rights: \par
}\pard \fs20\fi-720\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 On the internal level of every nation, respect for all rights takes on great importance, especially: the right to \softline
life at every stage of its existence; the rights of the family, as the basic social community, or "cell of \softline
society{\u8221\'94}; justice in employment relationships; the rights inherent in the life of the political community as \softline
such; the rights based on the transcendent vocation of the human being, beginning with the right of freedom \softline
to profess and practice one's own religious belief. }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Sollicitudo Rei Socialis}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  33.6: n.33.6. \par
}\pard \fs20\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 These rights protect the dignity of the person and enables individuals to flourish.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Ninth Basic Truth: Personalist Feminism is pro-life and pro-maternity. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab At all times, personalist feminism takes as its principle of specification, or proper action, the truths about \softline
women{\u8212\'97}including her ability to conceive and nurture new life. To kill her offspring, whether unborn or born, is thus \softline
to attack her femininity and demean her value as a woman as well as to destroy a new human life; it is utterly \softline
morally reprehensible. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Women are also attacked and trivialized whenever her reproductive powers are isolated and manipulated \softline
through biotechnology that farms her eggs for }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 in vitro}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  fertilizations and implants those fertilized eggs into the \softline
wombs of strangers. The reduction of maternity to a form of living biotechnology asserts that maternity is not a \softline
personal act whereby a woman{\u8217\'92}s love nurtures the little one but a productive act that lacks intrinsic value. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Such trivialization of maternity not only insults women (and thereby the Creator) but makes the child a \softline
product of technology. Thus, }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 in vitro}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  fertilization technologies trivialize the preciousness of human life and distort \softline
the basic truths of womanhood. In other words, since}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  women bring new life into the world, to be anti-life is to be \softline
anti-woman----just as, adopting artificial means of reproduction is also to be anti-woman. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab Denigrating the value of new human life and maternity (both physical and spiritual) disorient women and \softline
cause her to lose her way so that she does not know the joy of self-transcendent love typically achieved through \softline
sexual complementarity, spousal oneness and children.{}{\plain \fs24 \super 30{\footnote \pard \fs24\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 30}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   n. 10: {\u8220\'93}The revealed truth concerning the creation of the human being as male and female \softline
constitutes the principal argument against all the objectively injurious and unjust situations which contain and \softline
express the inheritance of the sin which all human beings bear within themselves.  The books of Sacred Scripture \softline
confirm in various places the actual existence of such situations and at the same time proclaim the need for \softline
conversion, that is to say, for purification from evil and liberation from sin: from what offends neighbor, what \softline
{\u8220\'93}diminishes{\u8221\'94} man, not only the one who is offended but also the one who causes the offence. This is the \softline
unchangeable message of the Word revealed by God.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  In such case, alienation from the wellspring of life \softline
frequently causes loneliness and heart ache. Yet, women without children or without spouses can still find joy, if \softline
they find a way to nurture life through their work or through volunteering. To so nurture life is to be a spiritual \softline
mother{\u8212\'97}that is, to be the best kind of mother who can help others become humane.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Tenth Truth: The Feminine Genius for Love Extends to the Spirit.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \tab The maternal orientation is the source of what John Paul II calls their feminine genius insofar as women not \softline
only are sensitive to the truth about others but also insofar as women can {\u8220\'93}ensure sensitivity for human beings in \softline
every circumstance.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 31{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 31}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  #30.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  And since it takes sensitivity to love effectively, it takes the genius of women to figure out \softline
how to best love others and enable them achieve ultimate fulfillment by union with God. For this reason, John Paul \softline
II speaks of women having a prophetic femininity that makes {\u8220\'93}manifest that very human being is loved by God in \softline
Christ.{\u8221\'94}{}{\plain \fs24 \super 32{\footnote \pard \fs20\sa240 
{\plain \fs24 \super 32}{}{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  #29.}}}
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  This means that women can be not only mothers in the flesh but also mothers in the spirit, as explained by \softline
John Paul II: \par
}\pard \fs20\li720\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Each and every time that motherhood is repeated in human history, it is always related to the Covenant \softline
which God established with the human race through the motherhood of the Mother of God. Does not Jesus \softline
bear witness to this reality which he answers the exclamation of that woman in the crowd who blessed him 
for Mary{\u8217\'92}s motherhood: {\u8216\'91}Blessed is the womb that bore you, and the breasts that you sucked{\u33\'21}{\u8221\'94}? Jesus \softline
replies: {\u8220\'93}Blessed rather are those who hear the word of God and keep it{\u8221\'94} (Lk 11:27-28).  Jesus confirms the \softline
meaning of motherhood in reference to the body, but at the same time he indicates an even deeper meaning, \softline
which is connected with the order of the spirit: it is a sign of the Covenant with God who {\u8216\'91}is spirit{\u8217\'92} (Jn \softline
4:24). . . .  The motherhood of every woman, understood in light of the Gospel, is similarly not only {\u8216\'91}of \softline
flesh and blood{\u8221\'94}: it expresses a profound {\u8216\'91}listening to the word of the living God{\u8217\'92} and a readiness to \softline
{\u8216\'91}safeguard{\u8217\'92} this Word.  }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Mulieris Dignitatem }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 #19.\par
